# Day 4 – Compliance: Following the Rules, But Not Mistaking Them for Security | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Building on the First Three Days

Day 1 introduced me to GRC as a whole. Day 2 taught me that governance sets the direction. Day 3 showed me how to think about risk. Today I reached the third pillar — **Compliance** — and it came with what I think is one of the most important lessons so far: compliance and security are not the same thing, and confusing the two can be genuinely dangerous.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Compliance, at its core, means following the laws, regulations, and standards that apply to your organization. In healthcare that means things like:

- **HIPAA** — the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, which sets the baseline for how patient data must be handled in the US
- **HITECH** — which strengthened HIPAA enforcement and introduced breach notification requirements
- **NIST frameworks** — which provide structured guidance for building security programs

For an OpenMRS deployment handling real patient data, HIPAA is the big one. It requires organizations to conduct risk analyses, limit access to electronic protected health information (ePHI), encrypt data appropriately, train staff on security, and have an incident response process in place.

That sounds like a solid security program. And it is — as a starting point. But here is the thing I kept running into today: HIPAA tells you *what* to do, not always *how* to do it well. The gap between meeting the requirement on paper and actually being secure in practice is where most organizations get into trouble.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The phrase that kept coming back to me today was simple:

**Compliance is the floor. Security is the ceiling.**

Compliance sets the minimum — the baseline you must meet to avoid legal penalties and regulatory fines. But meeting the minimum does not mean you are actually protected. An organization can tick every box on a HIPAA checklist and still be breached, because compliance is backward-looking by nature. It tells you what was required when the regulation was written. Attackers do not care about that.

Real security means going beyond the checklist — actively thinking about what your specific environment needs, what your actual risks are, and whether your controls would hold up under real pressure. Compliance points you in the right direction. Security is the work you do once you get there.

That distinction feels important enough that I want to carry it through the rest of this project.

---

## Applying This to OpenMRS on AWS

One of the HIPAA requirements I looked at today was **§164.308(a)(1)(ii)(A)** — the requirement to conduct an accurate and thorough assessment of potential risks and vulnerabilities to ePHI.

For an OpenMRS deployment on AWS, meeting that requirement means regularly checking things like:

- Are all software components — including the OpenMRS application and underlying server — patched and up to date?
- Is ePHI encrypted at rest and in transit?
- Who has access to patient data, and is that access reviewed regularly?
- Are audit logs in place so you can detect and investigate suspicious activity?

But here is the important part — doing those things just to satisfy the HIPAA checkbox misses the point. The reason to do them is because unpatched software gets exploited, unencrypted data gets stolen, and unreviewed access leads to insider incidents. The compliance requirement exists because those risks are real. The goal is to actually manage the risk, not just document that you reviewed it.

---

## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **Lifespan Health System breach** — a case that really illustrates the gap between compliance and real security. An unencrypted laptop was stolen, exposing the records of thousands of patients. Lifespan was fined over **$1 million** by the HHS Office for Civil Rights.

What struck me about this case is that HIPAA's encryption requirement for laptops is listed as "addressable" — meaning organizations are expected to implement it or document why they chose not to. Lifespan had not encrypted their devices and had not documented a reason. That is a compliance failure, but it is also a security failure that could have been prevented with a straightforward technical control.

I came across a pattern in breach reports that keeps repeating itself: organizations have policies on paper but fail to implement the practical controls behind them. Compliance becomes a documentation exercise rather than a genuine security effort. And when something goes wrong — as it did for Lifespan — the fines are the least of the consequences. Patient trust is harder to recover than money.

The question I keep sitting with after reading about cases like this is not *"are we compliant?"* but *"if someone tested our controls today, would they actually hold up?"* Those are very different questions.

